    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very prudent question to ask, especially since you are helping your dad. It is perfectly normal for him to start getting forgetful, but setting up a Durable Power of Attorney (DPOA) *now* is the smartest move he can make to protect his future self.\n\nThink of it like this: if he forgets to pay his mortgage because he's getting forgetful, a regular POA would just expire the moment he loses his mind. But a DPOA is like a \"keep the door open\" sign that stays up forever, ensuring that a trusted agent can still manage his bank accounts, pay his bills, and sign legal papers without the court having to step in and take over immediately.\n\nIf there isn't a DPOA in place, the situation can get tricky. Without it, a regular POA would likely expire once his mental capacity is lost, leaving his assets vulnerable. Someone else might not be able to step in to guard the money, or they might be reluctant to take over because they don't trust him anymore. A DPOA ensures that a trusted agent can still manage his financial affairs even if he becomes incapacitated.\n\nHowever, it's crucial to note that a",
