      "content": "That is a fantastic follow-up question, and it's exactly the kind of detail that makes a DPOA so much more valuable than a regular one.\n\nIf your dad doesn't have a Durable Power of Attorney in place, and he suddenly loses the capacity to manage his own affairs, the legal system will likely step in to appoint a **Guardian**. This is a different beast than a DPOA, and it can be a very stressful and expensive process for your dad.\n\nHere is how the guardian process usually works:\n1.  **The Petition:** Someone (usually a family member or a professional) files a petition with the court to appoint a guardian.\n2.  **The Hearing:** The court holds a hearing where they decide who is the best person to watch over his assets.\n3.  **The Appointment:** Once the court approves, the guardian is legally authorized to make decisions about his real estate, bank accounts, and daily living expenses.\n\n**The Catch:**\nA regular POA (even a durable one) is often *not* enough to stop a court from appointing a guardian. In many jurisdictions, the law requires a specific \"Guardianship Petition\" to be filed",
